<subSubSection box="[151,1292,825,850]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,825,1749]" box="[151,1292,825,850]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,826,850]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet alludes to the glandular condition of the supra-anal plate of the male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,825,1749]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,861,886]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
(Based mainly on comparisons with specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[896,1000,861,885]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Ottedana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[896,1000,861,885]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">Ottedana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Maxillary palpi short and robust, the last joint with a large apical truncation; male supra-anal plate with an unpigmented, nearly glabrous, membranous, area in central portion; male paraprocts without a cavity on ventral surface; male cerci without clasping structure; dorsum and laterals of the phallic complex covered by scutum-shaped membranous hood; pseudepiphallic parameres 
<number box="[272,286,1005,1029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number box="[340,354,1005,1029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
without inflatable membranous structure (cf. de 
<bibRefCitation author="Mello" box="[899,1166,1005,1029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" refString="De Mello, F. A. G., De Andrade, F. (2003) Ottedana cercalis: a new genus and species of phalangopsidae cricket from the Mantiqueira Range of Southeastern Brazil. (Orthoptera: Grylloidea). Journal of Orthoptera Research, 12 (2), 141 - 148." type="journal article" year="2003">
Mello &amp; Andrade, 
<number box="[1110,1166,1005,1029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
for this character). Ovipositor straight.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="38" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,825,1749]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1077,1102]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">Description.</emphasis>
Male: body sub-cylindrical, pubescent; back of head and fastigium with bristles and micro pilosity, its greatest width at eye level; inter-ocular space slightly flattened, oblique in lateral view; eye without unpigmented area (
<figureCitation box="[302,366,1149,1173]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1882,1905]" captionTargetBox="[195,1345,206,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[188,1398,195,1858]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Adenopygus heikoi Bolfarini &amp; de Mello sp. n. — male. A—dorsal view of body; B - frontal view of head; C—lateral view of head; D—maxillary palpi; E—perpendicular view of left eye; F, G—lateral and dorsal view of fore wings; H—lateral view of terminalia; I—supra-anal plate; J— subgenital plate." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210623/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[355,366,1149,1173]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
E); three ocelli present; maxillary palpi short, last joint with robust apical truncation occupying about half of its length (
<figureCitation box="[420,483,1185,1209]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1882,1905]" captionTargetBox="[195,1345,206,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[188,1398,195,1858]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Adenopygus heikoi Bolfarini &amp; de Mello sp. n. — male. A—dorsal view of body; B - frontal view of head; C—lateral view of head; D—maxillary palpi; E—perpendicular view of left eye; F, G—lateral and dorsal view of fore wings; H—lateral view of terminalia; I—supra-anal plate; J— subgenital plate." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210623/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[472,483,1185,1209]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D). Pronotum disk wider than long, covered with bristles, its anterior margin slightly concave, posterior margin straight; lateral lobes with straight ventral margin, antero-ventral angle of nearly 
<number box="[1408,1436,1221,1245]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="90.0">90</number>
degrees, postero-ventral angle rounded; fore wings short, not reaching posterior margin of metanotum, non-glandular, covered with bristles on posterior half and bearing trace of single longitudinal vein (
<figureCitation box="[1150,1213,1293,1317]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1882,1905]" captionTargetBox="[195,1345,206,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[188,1398,195,1858]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Adenopygus heikoi Bolfarini &amp; de Mello sp. n. — male. A—dorsal view of body; B - frontal view of head; C—lateral view of head; D—maxillary palpi; E—perpendicular view of left eye; F, G—lateral and dorsal view of fore wings; H—lateral view of terminalia; I—supra-anal plate; J— subgenital plate." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210623/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[1203,1213,1293,1317]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
F, G), internal margins juxtaposed, lateral margins gradually merging into posterior margin; dorsum of metanotum with granular area; tibia I armed with 
<number box="[360,374,1365,1389]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
ventral apical spurs, one internal and one external; tibia II with 
<number box="[1100,1114,1365,1389]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
apical spurs; tibia III with 
<number box="[1422,1436,1365,1389]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
dorsal spurs on both sides, 
<number box="[454,468,1401,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="3.0">3</number>
apical spurs on each side, of which median spur is the longest on the internal face and upper spur is the longest on the external. Supra-anal plate broad, glandular, densely haired (
<figureCitation box="[1207,1271,1437,1461]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1882,1905]" captionTargetBox="[195,1345,206,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[188,1398,195,1858]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Adenopygus heikoi Bolfarini &amp; de Mello sp. n. — male. A—dorsal view of body; B - frontal view of head; C—lateral view of head; D—maxillary palpi; E—perpendicular view of left eye; F, G—lateral and dorsal view of fore wings; H—lateral view of terminalia; I—supra-anal plate; J— subgenital plate." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210623/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[1261,1271,1437,1461]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
L and 
<number box="[1351,1365,1437,1461]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
K-M), paraprocts horizontally oriented, devoid of cavity on ventral face to accommodate pseudoepiphallic lateral spines (condition present in 
<taxonomicName box="[388,492,1509,1533]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Ottedana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[388,492,1509,1533]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">Ottedana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); cerci short, without claspers. Phallic complex (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1103,1509,1533]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[188,1386,226,1468]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,193,1495]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Adenopygus heikoi Bolfarini &amp; de Mello sp. n. A—ventral view of phallic complex; B—idem, dorsal view; Cidem, lateral view; D—idem, posterior view. Conventions: Ps. S. — pseudepiphallic spine; Ps. P. — pseudepiphallic paramere; M. C. — membranous cap; Ect. F. — ectophallic fold; Ect. Arc. — ectophallic arch; End. Ap. — endophallic apodeme; Ect. Ap. ectophallic apodeme; End. Scl. — endophallic sclerite; V. V. — ventral valves." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210625/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[1089,1103,1509,1533]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
) with membranous dorso-lateral cap covering much of pseudepiphallus; point of contact of pseudepiphallic parameres 
<number box="[1199,1213,1545,1569]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number box="[1274,1290,1545,1569]" pageId="1" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
, in posterior view, without spherical membranous structure; ectophallic apodemes short with broad, well developed arch, ectophallic fold short; endophallic sclerite small, bearing crest-shaped dorsal apodeme only. Female: similar to male but larger and less cylindrical; apterous; dorsum of head more rounded in lateral view; supra-anal plate not glandular; paraprocts not horizontal; posterior margin of subgenital plate with wide shallow concavity; ovipositor straight, apical valves small.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
